prevtext:
Assume that $H_{a,s}$ is invariant for $(b,\sigma,\mathbb W)$. Since $U|_{H_{a,s}}$ is one to one from $H_{a,s}$ into $D_{\nu}$, by Equality (\ref{necessary_viability_theorem_1}), $D_{\nu}$ is invariant for $(B,S,\mathbb W)$. So, by Lemma \ref{necessary_viability_lemma} :

\begin{displaymath}
B^{(\nu)}(x - x^{(\nu)}e_{\nu})\geqslant 0
\textrm{ and }
S_{\nu,.}(x - x^{(\nu)}e_{\nu}) = 0
\end{displaymath}

for every $x\in\mathbb R^d$. Let $k\in\llbracket 1,e\rrbracket$ and $x\in\partial H_{a,s}$ be arbitrarily chosen. Since $U|_{\partial H_{a,s}}$ is one to one from $\partial H_{a,s}$ into $\partial D_{\nu}$, $U(x)\in\partial D_{\nu}$. Therefore, by construction of $B$ and $S$ :

\begin{displaymath}
\langle b(x),s\rangle =
B^{(\nu)}(U(x))\geqslant 0
\end{displaymath}

and

\begin{eqnarray*}
 \langle\sigma_{.,k}(x),s\rangle & = &
 \sum_{j = 1}^{d}\sigma_{j,k}(x)s^{(j)}\\
 & = &
 S_{\nu,k}(U(x)) = 0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\textbf{Step 2.} Assume that there exists $y_0\in\partial K$ such that $y_0\not\in K_{b,\pm\sigma}$. Then, there exists $s\in N_K(y_0)$ such that :
